			<tr><td colspan="2"><hr /></td></tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				Jila is right.
<br />

<br />
Intel is the cheap, second rate solution right now. AMD caught them with their pants down and did a no-lube raping job that will remain legend for decades. Let me highlight the differences in the two architectures for you. If this sounds rampantly pro-AMD, realize it's because AMD is technically superior to Intel at this point, not because I am an AMD fanboy. Go back a few months in this forum and you'll find me bashing on AMD.
<br />

<br />
There are <a href="http://www.digit-life.com/articles2/athlon64fx-athlon64/index.html" target="_blank" class="postlink">enough</a> <a href="http://www.tomshardware.com/cpu/20040318/index.html" target="_blank" class="postlink">reviews</a> to <a href="http://www.anandtech.com/cpuchipsets/showdoc.html?i=2002" target="_blank" class="postlink">sink</a> the <a href="http://anandtech.com/linux/showdoc.aspx?i=2114" target="_blank" class="postlink">titanic</a> on this topic, so don't get the idea that this is just my opinion.
<br />

<br />
Bottom line.
<br />

<br />
Athlon 64 chips run in the 1.5-2GHz range, use less power, and cost less than Intel.
<br />
Athlon 64 chips universally outperform all of Intel's best offerings in 99.5% of all benchmarking categories in 32bit Windows.
<br />
Athlon 64 chips have hardware buffer overflow protection. This makes them inherently far more secure than anything Intel has to offer.
<br />
Athlon 64 chips will gain a nearly twofold speed boost over Intel's 32bit chips when running on a 64bit capable operating system. That's linux right now, and Windows XP 64bit sometime in 2005.
<br />
Multiprocessor configurations of Opteron 64bit processors absolutely CRUSH everything else on the market unless you go into mainfraime computing.
<br />

<br />
Intel got @#%$ because they got arrogant, and decided the industry would go their way, and stuck with 32bit. AMD somehow managed to build a 64bit chip that can run 32bit code natively, giving it universal backwards compatibility, and proved Intel wrong. Now, AMD will sit in the sunshine for a year or two while Intel frantically tries to engineer a processor that can compete with AMD. All of Intel's future business plans have been upset and scrapped at this point. They have no existing processor that can hope to compete with AMD's line of processors. The Prescott can't do it because it uses too much power; the design is flawed. The Itanium can't do it, because it's wholly incompatible with x86 computing. The Pentium-M (yeah, the mobile piece of @#%$) is their best bet, and that's pathetic. All of Intel's chips run too hot, use too much power, and Intel has NO 64bit architecture that is backwards compatible. They are forced instead to implement AMDs technology in their own chips.
<br />

<br />
Lately, Intel has been waging a very dirty press game. They promise things like "Pentium 4 3.6GHz Extreme Edition" which can just barely TIE AMD's best chips (that run at less than half the speed), yet you can't buy a P4 3.6GHz chip with a bag of rubies. All of Intel's top of the line products are one step from vaporware, and exist soley to make them look competitive in benchmarks. As far as we as consumers are concerned, those chips don't exist, because we can't buy them, and even if we could they'd be horribly expensive.
<br />

<br />
Intel has a big bank account. They can afford a year off, so they'll be back, rest assured. In the meantime, though, they are clearly the second rate CPU maker. AMd won this round by miles and miles. It's a good thing, too, because AMD had always been one step from bankruptcy. Now AMD is rolling on dough, and is finishing a 10 billion dollar processor factory in Germany. AMD is now firmly established as a competitior. Good on AMD. It means CPU price wars like the world has never seen, and we all win because we pay less.
<br />

<br />
Now, history lessons aside, this is what you need to know about buying a system.
<br />

<br />
AMD's 64 bit chips need a powerful motherboard. You need to buy motherboards that are supporting the "Socket 939" form factor, for the Athlon64 FX chips. That's your best bet for a single-CPU configuration. If you want a dual Opteron64 (like me), you will have to wait for Nvidia's Nforce4 line of chipsets, and motherboards based on them. They are not out yet, they should show up right around christmas and are going to drive prices on older stuff down.
<br />

<br />
The Nforce4 is the ultra-high end platform, and everyone is betting on it for the next generation of computing. Those motherboards won't look anything like what you see today, they are a next generation leap. If you have bank, that's what you want. If you are on a budget, you have two options, and they are going to cost you close to the same amount of money.
<br />

<br />
1) Buy an Intel P4 32bit (somewhat outdated) system on the cheap as the industry moves on and starts trying to get rid of the piles of that stuff sitting in warehouses. This is going to be damn cheap, but in two years it'll look like garbage because everything will be 64bit, and you'll notice it. Anyone who was around for the 16bit to 32bit switch (like me) will remember this @#%$. So far it's going MUCH more smoothly this time, and much faster, thanks largely to AMD's phenomenal backwards compatibility with 32bit code.
<br />

<br />
2) Buy an Athlon64 FX (more expensive) or Athlon 64 (less expensive) system. It'll run close to the same price as the Intel system (within $50 or so), and it'll perform just as well NOW. When the 64bit Windows hits the market, it'll get a big speed boost. Think of it as a free upgrade. You don't get that with Intel. You could also get that speed boost now with Linux, which has been 64bit-capable for years.
<br />

<br />
If you are a gamer, you want an Nforce4 or a Socket 939 with Athlon64 FX. Those processors are so fast, the only bottleneck is going to be the graphics card. No graphics card on the market right now can render as fast as those chips can pump data, and it'll be awhile before they can.
<br />

<br />
Now, if you are into the really sick, check this out. The Nforce4 has support for the oldschool SLI (scan line interleave) technology. This means you can hook up 2 or 4 of Nvidia's best graphics cards, and they will combine their power to draw one image on the monitor. This means if you have two cards, one draws the top and one draws the bottom. If you have four, one draws each quarter of the screen. This translates into a direct 200% or 400% boost to your graphics power. Direct. No loss of any kind.
<br />

<br />
That may sound nuts when you think of $500 graphics cards. Nvidia is promising its next line of PCIExpress cards (the ones that will do SLI) will retail, at the highest of the high end, for $300. So, you could do SLI for as cheap as $600 (only slightly more than some paid for a single ATI card last year).
<br />

<br />
The sweet spot will be an Nforce4 motherboard (prolly $170ish), an Athlon64 FX-? processor (prolly $600ish), and a pair of SLI-capable cards (prolly $600ish). For $1500ish you are looking at a computer that has more gaming and number crunching power by an order of magnitude than anything on the market last year. That means it's time to upgrade.
<br />

<br />
Or hold out for the Nforce4 mobo that has dual-cpu support ($250ish), a pair of Opteron chips for it (prolly $1200), and two or even four SLI cards ($600/$1200). You'd have a system that won't become obsolete for five years. Heck it won't even be <span style="font-style: italic">slow</span> for five years.
<br />

<br />
So, for gaming, now and for at least a year, AMD owns Intel. No contest.
<br />

<br />
Oh, and AMD's compatibility problems are history. The 64bit chips simply don't have them.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
			</td></tr>
		</table>
		</td>
	</tr>
