		<td width="150" align="left" valign="top" class="row2"><span class="name"><a name="81717"></a><b>EvilNight</b></span><br /><span class="postdetails">Agent of the System<br />
		<br /><img class="avatar" src="http://www.eqluclin.com/forum/images/avatars/bunbun.gif" alt="" /><br />
		<br />Joined: 19 Jul 2003<br />Posts: 2062</span></td>
		<td class="row2" width="100%" height="28" valign="top">

		<table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
			<tr>
			<td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><tr><td width="100%"><a href="viewtopic.php?p=81717&amp;sid=cccd1a50f0211ab99369aa2aa07f7854#81717"><img src="templates/eqluclin/images/icon_minipost.gif" width="12" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" border="0" /></a><span class="postdetails">Posted: Thu Aug 26, 2004 1:12 pm<span class="gen">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp; &nbsp;Post subject: Re: AMD 64 and Pentium 4.0ghz</span></td>
				<td width="30%" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap" align="right"> <a href="posting.php?mode=quote&amp;p=81717&amp;sid=cccd1a50f0211ab99369aa2aa07f7854"><img src="templates/eqluclin/images/lang_english/icon_quote.gif" alt="Reply with quote" title="Reply with quote" border="0" /></a>   </td></tr></table></td>
			</tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2"><hr /></td></tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> but the whole multiple video card deal, are we talking only the exact same card, or can you mix and match? </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Honestly I don't know. My suspicion would be that as long as the cards use the exact same driver (so as not to confuse the game or operating system) and support SLI, you could probably do it. Going any farther than that will probably require special drivers, SLI-native support in DirectX, and games that are at least aware of multiple cards when present. At first I'd bet you won't be able to, but by the second or third generation I'd bet you can mix and match. That's assuming SLI lasts a few generations. Last time they tried it, it was a blip that barely existed and nobody bought it, but then 3dfx was on the way out at the time too.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> I basically only check TomsHardware for benchmarks and the like, and I've heard the rumors that they are a bit biased sometimes, but AMD doesn't win nearly as many gaming benchmarks as you stated, according to them anyways </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Actually, check your link again and you see that only Intel's P4EE running at 3.4GHz can beat AMD's FX-53. The P4EE beats it by about 3%, and costs $200 more ($1000 vs $810). It's running twice as fast, and has four times the cache memory as the FX-53.  It also has no future 64bit support. I think AMD is a clear winner there.
<br />

<br />
As for being slow at old games, think of it this way. Those old games were written to run on Intel processors, and have a lot of optimization in them to take advantage of Intel's chips. AMD does not have that advantage, and still performs to within 3%. The more modern games are going to have AMD-specific optimizations now as Intel falls by the wayside. The scale is going to flip over. You can do a hell of a lot more with 64bit words in terms of optimization than you can with 32bit.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> my P4 system is still a lot better for ripping and encoding movies </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
You know, I've noticed that too. AMD chips encode like @#%$ (video, anyways). I can't even get Gordian Knot to RUN on my dual-AthlonXP system. Most of the encoders actually REQUIRE an Intel chip to function properly, and the ones that do support AMD aren't optimized for it. I think that'll change. 64bit vs 32bit encoding should look like night and day even on the same speed system. We're going to have to give the encoder software writers some time to update their software.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
			</td></tr>
		</table>
